flavorText: He loves to show off his vast knowledge. This expressive Pikachu is like a middle-aged man.
This Pokémon feeds on berries, whose leftover seeds become the ammunition for attacks it fires off from its mouth.
When the twig is plucked from its tail, friction sets the twig alight. The flame is used to send signals to its allies.
It doesn't do anything other than eat and sleep. When prompted to make a serious effort, though, it apparently displays awesome power.
In their search for comfortable trees, they get into territorial disputes with groups of Passimian. They win about half the time.
Although it has a violent disposition, if you give it a nice ripe fruit that it loves, Noivern will suddenly become tame.
This Pokémon feeds on berries, whose leftover seeds become the ammunition for attacks it fires off from its mouth.
It appears and vanishes with a ninja's grace. It toys with its enemies using swift movements, while slicing them with throwing stars of sharpest water.
It claws if displeased and purrs when affectionate. Its fickleness is very popular among some.
If it finds honey, its crescent mark glows. It always licks its paws because they are soaked with honey.
With its ability to distinguish any aroma, it unfailingly finds all food buried deep underground.
Very rarely, a sudden mutation can result in two small Koffing twins becoming conjoined as a Weezing.
By bending its beak, it can produce a variety of calls and brand itself a noisy nuisance for its neighbors.
It checks out whatever's around it by licking everything. If you don't clean off a spot where it's licked you, you'll break out in a rash!
It would claim another Pokémon's nest as its own if it finds a nest sufficiently comfortable.
It has feuded with Seviper for many generations. Its sharp claws are its biggest weapons.
It expels its internal steam from the arms on its back. It has enough power to blow away a mountain.
Usually it's a well-behaved Pokémon, but if you take its round rock away, it will cry and fuss and throw a big old tantrum.
A contest is under way to determine which one can stick its tongue out the farthest. The current record is…more than 82 feet.
Within its beak, its internal gas ignites, explosively launching seeds with enough power to pulverize boulders.
It mimics the cries of other Pokémon to trick them into thinking it's one of them. This way they won't attack it.
This Pokémon has excellent judgment. If it decides it can't defeat an opponent, it immediately turns tail and vamooses.
Kangaskhan protects its child by keeping it in its pouch. It has zero forgiveness for those who harm its child and will beat them down.
Magearna, with its metallic body, is an artificial Pokémon created 500 years ago by humans.
The longer its black fur grows, the harder and more impervious it gets. Claws and fangs can't easily penetrate it.
They live in groups. The one with the longest, thickest, and most-scarred horns is the boss of the herd.
It pays no mind to the cold, thanks to its long warm coat. Stoutland in Alola look a little uncomfortable.
It melts particles of iron and other metals found in the subsoil, so it can absorb them into its body of molten steel.
Every day, it tilts its head in the same rhythm. A long time ago, people raised these Pokémon to serve as clocks.
With its powerful legs and sturdy claws, it can crack even the hard shells of Shellder and pluck out their insides.
With eyes that can see in pitch-darkness, it never lets its prey escape. Some even call it "the emperor of dark nights."
It lets out billows of steam and disappears into the dense fog. It's said to live in mountains where humans do not tread.
The more scars it has on its front, the more heroic it's considered to be. Those with many scars on their back are mocked by the flock.
The way Slakoth lolls around makes anyone who watches it feel like doing the same.
It appeared from an Ultra Wormhole. Each one appears to be made up of many life-forms stacked one on top of each other.
They make their home in deserts. They can generate their energy from basking in the sun, so eating food is not a requirement.
The way Slakoth lolls around makes anyone who watches it feel like doing the same.
They flare their frills and generate energy. A single Heliolisk can generate sufficient electricity to power a skyscraper.
Its heartbeat is fast and its blood so agitated that it can't sit still for one second.
Revered long ago for its capacity to create iron from nothing, for some reason it has come back to life after 3,000 years.
It boasts power enough to split large trees in half. The organ on its rear releases an odor that it uses to communicate with others of its kind.
Although the jewel on its forehead appears to be a different color than those of Alolan Persian, it's mostly made of the same material.
The world's laziest Pokémon. It moves to another spot when there's no food left within its reach.
It's in its nature to store electricity. It feels stressed now and then if it's unable to fully discharge the electricity.
With nerves of steel, nothing can perturb it. It is more agile and active than it appears.
It waves its hands wildly in intimidation and warning. Life is over for anyone who doesn't run away as fast as possible.
Current studies show it can evolve into an incredible eight different species of Pokémon.
A Pokémon weapon developed for a specific mission, it went berserk during an experiment, so it was cryogenically frozen.
It busily makes its nest with stacks of branches and roots it has cut up with its sharp incisors.
It has a secret, devastating move. It rubs its blazing fur together to cause huge explosions.
It hides food under its long fur, but it sometimes forgets about it and causes a stinky disturbance.
If it inhales deeply, that's a sign it's about to attack. Prepare to be hit by flames of over 3,000 degrees Fahrenheit!
